The data I will be using is the World Happiness data from the year 2017 from the website, (https://www.kaggle.com/unsdsn/world-happiness/data). The variables I will focus on will be on the Health(life expectancy) and the variable Family, which is social support.

  1. As least two plots detailing the assumptions of your model, and multiple sentences describing how well (all) the assumptions of linear regression hold. Even if the assumptions are not met, continue with the rest of the assignment.
library(ggplot2)
hfReg <- lm(Family~Health_life_expectancy, data=Happines2017)
e <- rstandard(hfReg)
yhat_hf <- fitted(hfReg)
summary(hfReg)

The intercept of the firts regression plot was a round 0.78 with as slope of .74. These numbers are fairly close. In other words, this has a positive slope with more social support there tends to be a higher life expectancy.

  1. An interpretation of adjusted R2

The adjusted R^2 value is 0.3706. This means that 37.06% of the variation in Social support is explained by the least squares line on Health(Life expectancy)

  1. A formal hypothesis.

From our regression plot and reassuring that our regression assumptions have been met, with a positive slope in our regression line, it can be hypothesized that as Health(life expectancy) increase it tends to mean an increase in social support.

  1. A formal conclusion in both Statistics and such that my Grandmother could understand.

As we see a higher life expectancy in a country there tends to be more social support in that country.
